{"bloom_level": "analyze", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00006", "completion": "Two literals are equal as RDF literals when their values are equal in the datatype's value space — not when their lexical forms match character-for-character. This is one of the most easily missed details in RDF, because for plain strings the lexical and value spaces coincide. Learners should be able to break this down and explain the parts of literal.", "content_type": "rationale", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_2260af1accf5e1e4", "instruction_variant": 0, "lo_refs": ["co-02", "co-18", "to-01", "to-04"], "prompt": "Analyze the structure of literal and identify its most important relationships.", "provider": "mock", "requires_source_citation": false, "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 22, "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00006", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00006]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.3, "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s1"}, {"confidence": 0.95, "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_primer_accessible#s9"}, {"confidence": 0.85, "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_concepts_accessible#s2"}], "template_id": "analyze._default"}
