{"bloom_level": "apply", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00103", "completion": "The SPARQL 1.1 Query Language § 3 introduces FILTER like this: graph pattern matching produces a solution sequence, where each solution has a set of bindings of variables to RDF terms; SPARQL filters restrict solutions to those for which the filter expression evaluates to true . The mental model is therefore very simple: the BGP produces a multiset of solutions, and a FILTER is a predicate... A proficient learner can use this about three valued logic in a new but similar situation.", "content_type": "page-title", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_8145dd4a07e1edfd", "instruction_variant": 0, "lo_refs": ["co-12", "to-03"], "prompt": "Use the idea of three valued logic to resolve a realistic problem; describe both the problem and your approach.", "provider": "mock", "requires_source_citation": false, "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 119, "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00103", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00103]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.9, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:sparql11_query_accessible#b59dd96efbe6319e"}, {"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:sparql11_query_accessible#25ba4fe7efa83f42"}], "template_id": "apply._default"}
