{"bloom_level": "analyze", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00134", "completion": "The single most common bug in hand-written SPARQL aggregate queries is using FILTER where HAVING is required (or, less often, the reverse). The two clauses look syntactically similar — both take a boolean expression and drop the rows for which it is false — but they fire at radically different points in the evaluation pipeline, and the difference shows up the instant aggregate functions enter... Learners should be able to break this down and explain the parts of mental shorthand.", "content_type": "common_pitfall", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_ef049d1e46fec7c3", "instruction_variant": 0, "lo_refs": ["co-13", "to-03"], "prompt": "Analyze the structure of mental shorthand and identify its most important relationships.", "provider": "mock", "requires_source_citation": false, "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 150, "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00134", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00134]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s6"}], "template_id": "analyze._default"}
