{"bloom_level": "apply", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00121", "completion": "SPARQL 1.1 defines a fixed set of aggregate functions, each of which the specification calls a \"set function\" because it maps a multiset of values to a single value: COUNT(expr) — the number of bindings in the group for which expr evaluates without error. COUNT(*) counts solutions regardless of variable binding. A proficient learner can use this about reading strategy in a new but similar situation.", "content_type": "explanation", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_55739db264caa8ec", "instruction_variant": 0, "lo_refs": ["co-13", "to-03"], "prompt": "Describe a concrete situation where you would apply the concept of reading strategy, and say why.", "provider": "mock", "requires_source_citation": false, "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 137, "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00121", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00121]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s6"}], "template_id": "apply.explanation"}
